name: 2,3,3-trimethyl-2-butanol
source: Wilhoit R. C. Physical and Thermodynamic Properties of Aliphatic Alcohols. (Supplement to Journal of Physical and Chemical Reference Data; Vol 2; No. 1.); American Chemical Society; Washington; 1973.
Reason: The base structure for comparison is butanol, which has a melting point of -89.8 degrees Celsius. The following functional group modifications are made: each tert-butyl group (+75 due to sterically bulky and hinders crystal packing, thereby lowering the melting point), and the additional methyl group in the 3-position (+5 due to increased molecular weight and branching). The presence of two tert-butyl groups and an extra methyl introduces significant steric hindrance and branching, which typically increases the melting point compared to the linear butanol, by making the molecule more compact and improving its ability to pack in the solid state.

name: 2,3,3-trimethyl-2-butanol
source: Wilhoit R. C. Physical and Thermodynamic Properties of Aliphatic Alcohols. (Supplement to Journal of Physical and Chemical Reference Data; Vol 2; No. 1.); American Chemical Society; Washington; 1973.
Reason: To predict the melting point of 2,3,3-trimethyl-2-butanol, we consider the effects of various functional groups relative to a basic hydrocarbon chain. For a straight-chain butane, the melting point is approximately -0.5 degrees Celsius. First, the introduction of a hydroxyl group (OH) to form butanol generally increases the melting point due to hydrogen bonding which is very strong and significantly raises the melting point, we can estimate that as a +100 shift. However, the sterically hindered nature of the hydroxyl group in this molecule, being tertiary, might reduce the effectiveness of hydrogen bonding slightly, so we adjust this to about a +90 shift. Next, each methyl group branching will decrease the melting point. Branching tends to lower the melting point because it creates a structure that is less well-packed and therefore less crystalline, which in this case applies to the three additional methyl groups attached, estimated at a -20 each. Hence the net change due to the three methyl groups will be -60.

name: 2,3,3-trimethyl-2-butanol

Reason: To predict the melting point of 2,3,3-trimethyl-2-butanol, we should consider the cumulative effects of its functional groups. Starting with a basic hydrocarbon such as butane, which has a melting point of approximately -0.5°C, we add the effects of the functional groups found in 2,3,3-trimethyl-2-butanol. Firstly, the presence of a tertiary alcohol (OH) group tends to increase the melting point due to the possibility of hydrogen bonding, although the degree of increase is less for a tertiary alcohol compared to a primary one. We might estimate this as a +70 shift. Secondly, the effect of three additional methyl groups (making the compound highly branched), usually decreases the melting point because it disrupts the orderly packing of the molecules, reducing crystallinity. The effect of each methyl group could be estimated to cause a -10 shift. The compound has three extra methyl groups, leading to a total shift of -30. Summing these effects gives us a total shift of +40 from the base melting point of butane.
